problem:
Suppose that there are two congruent triangles $\triangle ABC$ and $\triangle ACD$ such that $AB = AC = AD,$ as shown in the following diagram. If $\angle BAC = 20^\circ,$ then what is $\angle BDC$? [asy]
pair pA, pB, pC, pD;
pA = (0, 0);
pB = pA + dir(240);
pC = pA + dir(260);
pD = pA + dir(280);
draw(pA--pB--pC--pA);
draw(pA--pC--pD--pA);
label("$A$", pA, N);
label("$B$", pB, SW);
label("$C$", pC, S);
label("$D$", pD, E);
[/asy]

solution:
First we draw $BD$: [asy]
pair pA, pB, pC, pD;
pA = (0, 0);
pB = pA + dir(240);
pC = pA + dir(260);
pD = pA + dir(280);
draw(pA--pB--pC--pA);
draw(pA--pC--pD--pA);
draw(pB--pD,red);
label("$A$", pA, N);
label("$B$", pB, SW);
label("$C$", pC, S);
label("$D$", pD, E);
[/asy] First, we see that $\triangle ABC$ is isosceles; therefore $\angle ACB = \angle ABC = \frac{1}{2}\cdot(180^{\circ}-20^\circ) = 80^\circ.$ Likewise, $\angle ACD = \angle ADC = 80^\circ.$ Now, we see that $\angle BCD = \angle ACB + \angle ACD = 160^\circ.$

Then, we see that $\triangle BCD$ is isosceles as well. That means $\angle CBD = \angle BDC = \frac{1}{2}\cdot(180^{\circ}-160^\circ) = \boxed{10^\circ},$ as desired.

